    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-11-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <head>329. Memorandum of Conversation Between the Under Secretary of State for
                    Political Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HWA1" type="from">Harriman</persName>)
                    and the Ambassador to Vietnam (<persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1" type="to"
                        >Lodge</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d329fn1">Source:
                            <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> Library, National
                        Security File, Vietnam Country File, Vietnam Cables. Secret; Eyes Only.
                        Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> on December
                        7.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1963-11-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 24, 1963</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>North Vietnam</item>
                </list>
                <p>Regarding <gloss target="#t_NVN1">NVN</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        >Lodge</persName>’s idea was that when <gloss target="#t_SVN1">SVN</gloss>
                    had made sufficient progress and clearly had the upper hand, we should first get
                    word to <gloss target="#t_NVN1">NVN</gloss>, in the form of a plant, that we
                    planned an air strike if <gloss target="#t_NVN1">NVN</gloss> did not stop their
                    support of the Viet-Cong, and then develop some method by which, after they were
                    in a fearful mood, direct contact would be made which would get them to stop
                    support in return for our abandoning plans for striking <gloss target="#t_NVN1"
                        >NVN</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> believes <gloss
                        target="#t_NVN1">NVN</gloss> both fears American air attack and having to
                    call on Red China for support, as <gloss target="#t_NVN1">NVN</gloss> feels they
                    would never be able to get Red China out.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> agreed to let me know when he
                    thought an opportunity had come to consider action along the above lines.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
